# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: gdb-debugging
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:gdb-debugging/addresssanitizer] A **code sanitizer** is a programming tool that detects bugs in the form of undefined or suspicious behavior by a compiler inserting instrumentation code at runtime.
[src:gdb-debugging/addresssanitizer] As of 2024, the most popular sanitizer is ASan, originally designed by Google.
[src:gdb-debugging/addresssanitizer] It is integrated into most mainstream compilers due to its relatively small memory and performance overhead.
[src:gdb-debugging/addresssanitizer] Google's ASan, introduced in 2012, uses a shadow memory scheme to detect memory bugs.
[src:gdb-debugging/addresssanitizer] The original design of the sanitizer increases processing time by about 73% and memory usage by 240%.
[src:gdb-debugging/addresssanitizer] There is a hardware-accelerated ASan called HWAsan available for AArch64 and (in a limited fashion) x86_64.
[src:gdb-debugging/addresssanitizer] AddressSanitizer does not detect any uninitialized memory reads (but this is detected by MemorySanitizer), and detects only some use-after-return bugs.
[src:gdb-debugging/addresssanitizer] It is also not capable of detecting all arbitrary memory corruption bugs, nor all arbitrary write bugs due to integer underflow/overflows (when the integer with undefined behavior is used to calculate memory address offsets).
[src:gdb-debugging/addresssanitizer] Adjacent buffers in structs and classes are not protected from overflow, in part to prevent breaking backwards compatibility.
[src:gdb-debugging/addresssanitizer] The **KernelAddressSanitizer** (**KASan**) detects dynamic memory errors in the Linux kernel.
[src:gdb-debugging/addresssanitizer] Kernel instrumentation requires a special feature in the compiler supplying the -fsanitize=kernel-address command line option, since kernels do not use the same address space as normal programs.
[src:gdb-debugging/addresssanitizer] KASan is also available for use with Windows kernel drivers beginning in Windows 11 22H2 and above.
[src:gdb-debugging/addresssanitizer] Similarly to Linux, compiling a Windows driver with KASAN requires passing the /fsanitize=kernel-address command line option to the MSVC compiler.
[src:gdb-debugging/addresssanitizer] Google also produced **LeakSanitizer** (LSan, memory leaks), **ThreadSanitizer** (TSan, data races and deadlocks), **MemorySanitizer** (MSan, uninitialized memory), and **UndefinedBehaviorSanitizer** (**UBSan**, undefined behaviors, with fine-grained control).
[src:gdb-debugging/addresssanitizer] These tools are generally available in Clang/LLVM and GCC.
[src:gdb-debugging/addresssanitizer] Similar to KASan, there are kernel-specific versions of LSan, MSan, TSan, as well as completely original kernel sanitizers such as KFENCE and KCSan.
[src:gdb-debugging/addresssanitizer] A code sanitizer detects suspicious behavior as the program runs.
[src:gdb-debugging/addresssanitizer] One common way to use a sanitizer is to combine it with fuzzing, which generates inputs likely to trigger bugs.
[src:gdb-debugging/addresssanitizer] Chromium and Firefox developers are active users of AddressSanitizer; the tool has found hundreds of bugs in these web browsers.
[src:gdb-debugging/addresssanitizer] A number of bugs were found in FFmpeg and FreeType.
[src:gdb-debugging/addresssanitizer] The Linux kernel has enabled the AddressSanitizer for the x86-64 architecture as of Linux version 4.0.
[src:gdb-debugging/breakpoint] In software development, a **breakpoint** is an intentional stopping or pausing place in a program, put in place for debugging purposes.
[src:gdb-debugging/breakpoint] It is also sometimes simply referred to as a **pause**.
[src:gdb-debugging/breakpoint] More generally, a breakpoint is a means of acquiring knowledge about a program during its execution.
[src:gdb-debugging/breakpoint] During the interruption, the programmer inspects the test environment (general-purpose registers, memory, logs, files, etc.) to determine whether the program is functioning as expected.
[src:gdb-debugging/breakpoint] In practice, a breakpoint consists of one or more conditions that determine when a program's execution should be interrupted.
[src:gdb-debugging/breakpoint] Breakpoints were invented for ENIAC, one of the earliest digital computers, by programmer Betty Holberton.
[src:gdb-debugging/breakpoint] In the initial design of ENIAC, program flow was set by plugging cables from one unit to another.
[src:gdb-debugging/breakpoint] To make the program stop at a certain point, a cable was removed, called a *breakpoint*.
[src:gdb-debugging/breakpoint] Early mainframe computers, such as the IBM/360, had console switches/dials that allowed breakpoints at specific instruction storage addresses and provided "single cycle" operation, permitting the contents of registers and memory to be observed directly on console lights.
[src:gdb-debugging/breakpoint] The advent of multitasking limited the use of this option since the entire machine was halted.
[src:gdb-debugging/breakpoint] Programmers have used machine code patches to implement single destructive breakpoints to cause a core dump since the early days of computers.
[src:gdb-debugging/breakpoint] The core dump provided the state of the registers and memory at the exact moment of the deliberate "crash".
[src:gdb-debugging/breakpoint] This also permitted step-by-step program execution in a true program animation manner with optional register and memory alterations simultaneously displayed.
[src:gdb-debugging/breakpoint] Initially this type of animation was at the level of disassembled or decompiled machine code, but later advanced to HLL source level animation.
[src:gdb-debugging/breakpoint] Breakpoints are most commonly used to interrupt a running program immediately before the execution of a programmer-specified instruction.
[src:gdb-debugging/breakpoint] This is often referred to as an *instruction breakpoint*.
[src:gdb-debugging/breakpoint] Other kinds of conditions can also be used, such as the reading, writing, or modification of a specific location in an area of memory.
[src:gdb-debugging/breakpoint] This is often referred to as a *data breakpoint*, or a *watchpoint*.
[src:gdb-debugging/breakpoint] Many systems also support breakpoints that are only active if a condition is met (such as a variable having a certain value), usually referred to as *conditional breakpoint*.
[src:gdb-debugging/breakpoint] When a breakpoint is hit, various tools are used to inspect the state of the program or alter it.
[src:gdb-debugging/breakpoint] Stack trace of each thread may be used to see the chain of function calls that led to the paused instruction.
[src:gdb-debugging/breakpoint] A list of *watches* allows one to view the values of selected variables and expressions.
[src:gdb-debugging/breakpoint] There may also be tools to show the contents of registers, loaded program modules and other information.
[src:gdb-debugging/breakpoint] A *logpoint* is a type of breakpoint that only prints (or "logs") information instead of interrupting execution.
[src:gdb-debugging/breakpoint] Usually the developer can specify a message and/or values of variables to print when execution reaches a specific point.
[src:gdb-debugging/breakpoint] Logpoints are an alternative to putting logging statements into the program being debugged (sometimes called *printf debugging*), and particularly helpful when changing the program is not practical (for example when debugging an external library called by the program).
[src:gdb-debugging/breakpoint] Many processors include hardware support for breakpoints (typically instruction and data breakpoints).
[src:gdb-debugging/breakpoint] As an example, the x86 instruction set architecture provides hardware support for breakpoints with its x86 debug registers.
[src:gdb-debugging/breakpoint] Such hardware may include limitations, for example not allowing breakpoints on instructions located in branch delay slots.
[src:gdb-debugging/breakpoint] This kind of limitation is imposed by the microarchitecture of the processor and varies from processor to processor.
[src:gdb-debugging/breakpoint] Without hardware support (and in multitasking environments), debuggers have to implement breakpoints in software.
[src:gdb-debugging/breakpoint] This technique may be more difficult to implement in multitasking systems using shared program storage (the interrupt may occur on a different thread, requiring resurrection of the original instruction for that thread).
[src:gdb-debugging/breakpoint] Also, if the program resides in protected memory, overwriting of instructions may be prevented.
[src:gdb-debugging/breakpoint] Some debuggers allow registers or program variables in memory to be modified before resuming, effectively allowing the introduction of "hand-coded" temporary assignments for test purposes.
[src:gdb-debugging/breakpoint] Similarly, program instructions can often be skipped to determine the effect of changes to the program logic – enabling questions about program execution to be answered in a direct way (i.e. without assumptions or guesswork).
[src:gdb-debugging/breakpoint] In many cases it may be the only practical method of testing obscure "event-driven" error subroutines that rarely, if ever, get executed – without the added risk of leaving temporary source changes.
[src:gdb-debugging/breakpoint] Manually changing the resume location within a paused program can be used to enter an otherwise rarely executed section of code (such as a specific hardware condition handler).
[src:gdb-debugging/breakpoint] Implementing data breakpoints in software however, can greatly reduce the performance of the application being debugged – since it is using additional resources on the same processor.
[src:gdb-debugging/breakpoint] However, this is normally acceptable during testing and the amount of information available from the debugger is not restricted by limitations of debug data known to the hardware.
[src:gdb-debugging/breakpoint] For instance, a software implementation can collect logical path data at program/subroutine/instruction level to considerably augment what might be stored by the particular hardware platform for inspection.
[src:gdb-debugging/breakpoint] The instruction set simulation method considerably reduces the overhead, compared to the (repeated) instruction replacement method, also reducing cache misses.
[src:gdb-debugging/breakpoint] Some programming language implementations expose their debugging functions for use by other programs.
[src:gdb-debugging/breakpoint] For example, some FORTRAN dialects have an `AT` statement, which was originally intended to act as an instruction breakpoint.
[src:gdb-debugging/breakpoint] Python implements a debugger accessible from a Python program.
[src:gdb-debugging/breakpoint] These facilities can be and are abused to act like the COMEFROM statement.
[src:gdb-debugging/core-dump] In computing, a **core dump**, **memory dump**, **crash dump**, **storage dump**, **system dump**, or **ABEND dump** consists of the recorded state of the working memory of a computer program at a specific time, generally when the program has crashed or otherwise terminated abnormally.
[src:gdb-debugging/core-dump] In practice, other key pieces of program state are usually dumped at the same time, including the processor registers, which may include the program counter and stack pointer, memory management information, and other processor and operating system flags and information.
[src:gdb-debugging/core-dump] A **snapshot dump** (or **snap dump**) is a memory dump requested by the computer operator or by the running program, after which the program is able to continue.
[src:gdb-debugging/core-dump] Core dumps are often used to assist in diagnosing and debugging errors in computer programs.
[src:gdb-debugging/core-dump] On many operating systems, a fatal exception in a program automatically triggers a core dump.
[src:gdb-debugging/core-dump] By extension, the phrase "to dump core" has come to mean in many cases, any fatal error, regardless of whether a record of the program memory exists.
[src:gdb-debugging/core-dump] The term "core dump", "memory dump", or just "dump" has also become jargon to indicate any output of a large amount of raw data for further examination or other purposes.
[src:gdb-debugging/core-dump] The name comes from magnetic-core memory, the principal form of random-access memory from the 1950s to the 1970s.
[src:gdb-debugging/core-dump] The name has remained long after magnetic-core technology became obsolete.
[src:gdb-debugging/core-dump] Earliest core dumps were paper printouts of the contents of memory, typically arranged in columns of octal or hexadecimal numbers (a "hex dump"), sometimes accompanied by their interpretations as machine language instructions, text strings, or decimal or floating-point numbers (*cf.* disassembler).
[src:gdb-debugging/core-dump] As memory sizes increased and post-mortem analysis utilities were developed, dumps were written to magnetic media like tape or disk.
[src:gdb-debugging/core-dump] In some operating systems an application or operator may request a snapshot of selected storage blocks, rather than all of the storage used by the application or operating system.
[src:gdb-debugging/core-dump] Core dumps can serve as useful debugging aids in several situations.
[src:gdb-debugging/core-dump] On early standalone or batch-processing systems, core dumps allowed a user to debug a program without monopolizing the (very expensive) computing facility for debugging; a printout could also be more convenient than debugging using front panel switches and lights.
[src:gdb-debugging/core-dump] On shared computers, whether time-sharing, batch processing, or server systems, core dumps allow off-line debugging of the operating system, so that the system can go back into operation immediately.
[src:gdb-debugging/core-dump] Core dumps allow a user to save a crash for later or off-site analysis, or comparison with other crashes.
[src:gdb-debugging/core-dump] For embedded computers, it may be impractical to support debugging on the computer itself, so analysis of a dump may take place on a different computer.
[src:gdb-debugging/core-dump] Some operating systems such as early versions of Unix did not support attaching debuggers to running processes, so core dumps were necessary to run a debugger on a process's memory contents.
[src:gdb-debugging/core-dump] Core dumps can be used to capture data freed during dynamic memory allocation and may thus be used to retrieve information from a program that is no longer running.
[src:gdb-debugging/core-dump] In the absence of an interactive debugger, the core dump may be used by an assiduous programmer to determine the error from direct examination.
[src:gdb-debugging/core-dump] Snap dumps are sometimes a convenient way for applications to record quick and dirty debugging output.
[src:gdb-debugging/core-dump] A core dump generally represents the complete contents of the dumped regions of the address space of the dumped process.
[src:gdb-debugging/core-dump] Depending on the operating system, the dump may contain few or no data structures to aid interpretation of the memory regions.
[src:gdb-debugging/core-dump] In these systems, successful interpretation requires that the program or user trying to interpret the dump understands the structure of the program's memory use.
[src:gdb-debugging/core-dump] There are also special-purpose tools called dump analyzers to analyze dumps.
[src:gdb-debugging/core-dump] One popular tool, available on many operating systems, is the GNU binutils' objdump.
[src:gdb-debugging/core-dump] On modern Unix-like operating systems, administrators and programmers can read core dump files using the GNU Binutils Binary File Descriptor library (BFD), and the GNU Debugger (gdb) and objdump that use this library.
[src:gdb-debugging/core-dump] Analysts of crash dumps from Linux systems can use kdump or the Linux Kernel Crash Dump (LKCD).
[src:gdb-debugging/core-dump] Core dumps can save the context (state) of a process at a given state for returning to it later.
[src:gdb-debugging/core-dump] Systems can be made highly available by transferring core between processors, sometimes via core dump files themselves.
[src:gdb-debugging/core-dump] Core can also be dumped onto a remote host over a network (which is a security risk).
[src:gdb-debugging/core-dump] OS/360 introduced the service aid IMDPRDMP to print stand-alone and SVC dumps.
[src:gdb-debugging/core-dump] This program formats several system control blocks in addition to printing storage areas in hexadecimal and EBCDIC.
[src:gdb-debugging/core-dump] The OS/VS1 and OS/VS2 versions are called HMDPRDMP and AMDPRDMP.
[src:gdb-debugging/core-dump] Interactive Problem Control System (IPCS) is a full screen dump reader that IBM introduced for OS/VS2 (MVS), DOS/VSE and VM/370.
[src:gdb-debugging/core-dump] The MVS version performs functions similar to AMDPRDMP, and uses compatible control block descriptions for formatting.
[src:gdb-debugging/core-dump] IBM eventually dropped AMDPRDMP in favor of IPCS.
[src:gdb-debugging/core-dump] IPCS on MVS supports scripts in CLIST and REXX.
[src:gdb-debugging/core-dump] Users of IBM mainframes running z/OS can browse both SVC and transaction dumps using IPCS, which supports user written scripts in REXX and supports point-and-shoot browsing of dumps.
[src:gdb-debugging/core-dump] In older and simpler operating systems, each process had a contiguous address-space, so a dump file was sometimes simply a file with the sequence of bytes, digits, characters or words.
[src:gdb-debugging/core-dump] On other systems a dump file contained discrete records, each containing a storage address and the associated contents.
[src:gdb-debugging/core-dump] On the earliest of these machines, the dump was often written by a stand-alone dump program rather than by the application or the operating system.
[src:gdb-debugging/core-dump] The IBSYS monitor for the IBM 7090 included a System Core-Storage Dump Program that supported post-mortem and snap dumps.
[src:gdb-debugging/core-dump] On the IBM System/360, the standard operating systems wrote formatted ABEND and SNAP dumps, with the addresses, registers, storage contents, etc., all converted into printable forms.
[src:gdb-debugging/core-dump] In modern operating systems, a process address space may contain gaps, and it may share pages with other processes or files, so more elaborate representations are used; they may also include other information about the state of the program at the time of the dump.
[src:gdb-debugging/core-dump] In OS/360 and successors, a job may assign arbitrary data set names (dsnames) to the ddnames `SYSABEND` and `SYSUDUMP` for a formatted ABEND dump and to arbitrary ddnames for SNAP dumps, or define those ddnames as SYSOUT.
[src:gdb-debugging/core-dump] The Damage Assessment and Repair (DAR) facility added an automatic unformatted storage dump to the dataset `SYS1.DUMP` at the time of failure as well as a console dump requested by the operator.
[src:gdb-debugging/core-dump] A job may assign an arbitrary dsname to the ddname `SYSMDUMP` for an unformatted ABEND dump, or define that ddname as SYSOUT.
[src:gdb-debugging/core-dump] The newer transaction dump is very similar to the older SVC dump.
[src:gdb-debugging/core-dump] The *Interactive Problem Control System* (IPCS), added to OS/VS2 by *Selectable Unit* (SU) 57 and part of every subsequent MVS release, can be used to interactively analyze storage dumps on DASD.
[src:gdb-debugging/core-dump] IPCS understands the format and relationships of system control blocks, and can produce a formatted display for analysis.
[src:gdb-debugging/core-dump] The current versions of IPCS allow inspection of active address spaces without first taking a storage dump and of unformaated dumps on SPOOL.
[src:gdb-debugging/core-dump] Since Solaris 8, system utility `coreadm` allows the name and location of core files to be configured.
[src:gdb-debugging/core-dump] Dumps of user processes are traditionally created as `core`.
[src:gdb-debugging/core-dump] System-wide dumps on modern Unix-like systems often appear as `vmcore` or `vmcore.incomplete`.
[src:gdb-debugging/core-dump] Systems such as Microsoft Windows, which use filename extensions, may use extension `.dmp`; for example, core dumps may be named `memory.dmp` or `\Minidump\Mini051509-01.dmp`.
[src:gdb-debugging/core-dump] Microsoft Windows supports two memory dump formats, described below.
[src:gdb-debugging/core-dump] To analyze the Windows kernel-mode dumps Debugging Tools for Windows are used, a set that includes tools like WinDbg & DumpChk.
[src:gdb-debugging/core-dump] User-mode memory dump, also known as *minidump*, is a memory dump of a single process.
[src:gdb-debugging/core-dump] It contains selected data records: full or partial (filtered) process memory; list of the threads with their call stacks and state (such as registers or TEB); information about handles to the kernel objects; list of loaded and unloaded libraries.
[src:gdb-debugging/core-dump] Full list of options available in `MINIDUMP_TYPE` enum.
[src:gdb-debugging/core-dump] The NASA Voyager program was probably the first craft to routinely utilize the core dump feature in the Deep Space segment.
[src:gdb-debugging/core-dump] The core dump feature is a mandatory telemetry feature for the Deep Space segment as it has been proven to minimize system diagnostic costs.
[src:gdb-debugging/core-dump] The Voyager craft uses routine core dumps to spot memory damage from cosmic ray events.
[src:gdb-debugging/core-dump] Space Mission core dump systems are mostly based on existing toolkits for the target CPU or subsystem.
[src:gdb-debugging/core-dump] However, over the duration of a mission the core dump subsystem may be substantially modified or enhanced for the specific needs of the mission.
[src:gdb-debugging/debugging] In engineering, **debugging** is the process of finding the root cause, workarounds, and possible fixes for bugs.
[src:gdb-debugging/debugging] For software, debugging tactics can involve interactive debugging, control flow analysis, log file analysis, monitoring at the application or system level, memory dumps, and profiling.
[src:gdb-debugging/debugging] Many programming languages and software development tools also offer programs to aid in debugging, known as debuggers.
[src:gdb-debugging/debugging] The term *bug*, in the sense of defect, dates back at least to 1878 when Thomas Edison wrote "little faults and difficulties" in his inventions as "Bugs".
[src:gdb-debugging/debugging] A popular story from the 1940's is from Admiral Grace Hopper.
[src:gdb-debugging/debugging] While she was working on a Mark II computer at Harvard University, her associates discovered a moth stuck in a relay that impeded operation and wrote in a log book "First actual case of a bug being found".
[src:gdb-debugging/debugging] Although probably a joke, conflating the two meanings of bug (biological and defect), the story indicates that the term was used in the computer field at that time.
[src:gdb-debugging/debugging] Similarly, the term *debugging* was used in aeronautics before entering the world of computers.
[src:gdb-debugging/debugging] Robert Oppenheimer, director of the WWII atomic bomb Manhattan Project at Los Alamos, used the term in a letter to Dr.
[src:gdb-debugging/debugging] Ernest Lawrence at UC Berkeley, dated October 27, 1944, regarding the recruitment of additional technical staff.
[src:gdb-debugging/debugging] The Oxford English Dictionary entry for *debug* uses the term *debugging* in reference to airplane engine testing in a 1945 article in the Journal of the Royal Aeronautical Society.
[src:gdb-debugging/debugging] 50) refers to *debugging* aircraft cameras.
[src:gdb-debugging/debugging] The seminal article by Gill in 1951 is the earliest in-depth discussion of programming errors, but it does not use the term *bug* or *debugging*.
[src:gdb-debugging/debugging] In the ACM's digital library, the term *debugging* is first used in three papers from the 1952 ACM National Meetings.
[src:gdb-debugging/debugging] Two of the three use the term in quotation marks.
[src:gdb-debugging/debugging] By 1963, *debugging* was a common enough term to be mentioned in passing without explanation on page 1 of the CTSS manual.
[src:gdb-debugging/debugging] As software and electronic systems have become generally more complex, the various common debugging techniques have expanded with more methods to detect anomalies, assess impact, and schedule software patches or full updates to a system.
[src:gdb-debugging/debugging] The words "anomaly" and "discrepancy" can be used, as being more neutral terms, to avoid the words "error" and "defect" or "bug" where there might be an implication that all so-called *errors*, *defects* or *bugs* must be fixed (at all costs).
[src:gdb-debugging/debugging] Instead, an impact assessment can be made to determine if changes to remove an *anomaly* (or *discrepancy*) would be cost-effective for the system, or perhaps a scheduled new release might render the change(s) unnecessary.
[src:gdb-debugging/debugging] Not all issues are safety-critical or mission-critical in a system.
[src:gdb-debugging/debugging] Also, it is important to avoid the situation where a change might be more upsetting to users, long-term, than living with the known problem(s) (where the "cure would be worse than the disease").
[src:gdb-debugging/debugging] Basing decisions of the acceptability of some anomalies can avoid a culture of a "zero-defects" mandate, where people might be tempted to deny the existence of problems so that the result would appear as zero *defects*.
[src:gdb-debugging/debugging] Considering the collateral issues, such as the cost-versus-benefit impact assessment, then broader debugging techniques will expand to determine the frequency of anomalies (how often the same "bugs" occur) to help assess their impact to the overall system.
[src:gdb-debugging/debugging] Debugging ranges in complexity from fixing simple errors to performing lengthy and tiresome tasks of data collection, analysis, and scheduling updates.
[src:gdb-debugging/debugging] Debuggers are software tools which enable the programmer to monitor the execution of a program, stop it, restart it, set breakpoints, and change values in memory.
[src:gdb-debugging/debugging] The term *debugger* can also refer to the person who is doing the debugging.
[src:gdb-debugging/debugging] Generally, high-level programming languages, such as Java, make debugging easier, because they have features such as exception handling and type checking that make real sources of erratic behaviour easier to spot.
[src:gdb-debugging/debugging] In programming languages such as C or assembly, bugs may cause silent problems such as memory corruption, and it is often difficult to see where the initial problem happened.
[src:gdb-debugging/debugging] In those cases, memory debugger tools may be needed.
[src:gdb-debugging/debugging] In certain situations, general purpose software tools that are language specific in nature can be very useful.
[src:gdb-debugging/debugging] These take the form of *static code analysis tools*.
[src:gdb-debugging/debugging] These tools look for a very specific set of known problems, some common and some rare, within the source code, concentrating more on the semantics (e.g. data flow) rather than the syntax, as compilers and interpreters do.
[src:gdb-debugging/debugging] Both commercial and free tools exist for various languages; some claim to be able to detect hundreds of different problems.
[src:gdb-debugging/debugging] These tools can be extremely useful when checking very large source trees, where it is impractical to do code walk-throughs.
[src:gdb-debugging/debugging] A typical example of a problem detected would be a variable dereference that occurs *before* the variable is assigned a value.
[src:gdb-debugging/debugging] As another example, some such tools perform strong type checking when the language does not require it.
[src:gdb-debugging/debugging] Thus, they are better at locating likely errors in code that is syntactically correct.
[src:gdb-debugging/debugging] But these tools have a reputation of false positives, where correct code is flagged as dubious.
[src:gdb-debugging/debugging] The old Unix *lint* program is an early example.
[src:gdb-debugging/debugging] For debugging electronic hardware (e.g., computer hardware) as well as low-level software (e.g., BIOSes, device drivers) and firmware, instruments such as oscilloscopes, logic analyzers, or in-circuit emulators (ICEs) are often used, alone or in combination.
[src:gdb-debugging/debugging] An ICE may perform many of the typical software debugger's tasks on low-level software and firmware.
[src:gdb-debugging/debugging] The debugging process normally begins with identifying the steps to reproduce the problem.
[src:gdb-debugging/debugging] This can be a non-trivial task, particularly with parallel processes and some Heisenbugs for example.
[src:gdb-debugging/debugging] The specific user environment and usage history can also make it difficult to reproduce the problem.
[src:gdb-debugging/debugging] After the bug is reproduced, the input of the program may need to be simplified to make it easier to debug.
[src:gdb-debugging/debugging] For example, a bug in a compiler can make it crash when parsing a large source file.
[src:gdb-debugging/debugging] However, after simplification of the test case, only few lines from the original source file can be sufficient to reproduce the same crash.
[src:gdb-debugging/debugging] Simplification may be done manually using a divide-and-conquer approach, in which the programmer attempts to remove some parts of original test case then checks if the problem still occurs.
[src:gdb-debugging/debugging] When debugging in a GUI, the programmer can try skipping some user interaction from the original problem description to check if the remaining actions are sufficient for causing the bug to occur.
[src:gdb-debugging/debugging] After the test case is sufficiently simplified, a programmer can use a debugger tool to examine program states (values of variables, plus the call stack) and track down the origin of the problem(s).
[src:gdb-debugging/debugging] In simple cases, tracing is just a few print statements which output the values of variables at particular points during the execution of the program.
[src:gdb-debugging/debugging] Automatic bug-fixing is the automatic repair of software bugs without the intervention of a human programmer.
[src:gdb-debugging/debugging] It is also commonly referred to as *automatic patch generation*, *automatic bug repair*, or *automatic program repair*.
[src:gdb-debugging/debugging] The typical goal of such techniques is to automatically generate correct patches to eliminate bugs in software programs without causing software regression.
[src:gdb-debugging/debugging] In contrast to the general purpose computer software design environment, a primary characteristic of embedded environments is the sheer number of different platforms available to the developers (CPU architectures, vendors, operating systems, and their variants).
[src:gdb-debugging/debugging] Embedded systems are, by definition, not general-purpose designs: they are typically developed for a single task (or small range of tasks), and the platform is chosen specifically to optimize that application.
[src:gdb-debugging/debugging] Not only does this fact make life tough for embedded system developers, it also makes debugging and testing of these systems harder as well, since different debugging tools are needed for different platforms.
[src:gdb-debugging/debugging] Despite the challenge of heterogeneity mentioned above, some debuggers have been developed commercially as well as research prototypes.
[src:gdb-debugging/debugging] Examples of commercial solutions come from Green Hills Software, Lauterbach GmbH and Microchip's MPLAB-ICD (for in-circuit debugger).
[src:gdb-debugging/debugging] Two examples of research prototype tools are Aveksha and Flocklab.
[src:gdb-debugging/debugging] They all leverage a functionality available on low-cost embedded processors, an On-Chip Debug Module (OCDM), whose signals are exposed through a standard JTAG interface.
[src:gdb-debugging/debugging] They are benchmarked based on how much change to the application is needed and the rate of events that they can keep up with.
[src:gdb-debugging/debugging] Anti-debugging is "the implementation of one or more techniques within computer code that hinders attempts at reverse engineering or debugging a target process".
[src:gdb-debugging/debugging] It is actively used by recognized publishers in copy-protection schemas, but is also used by malware to complicate its detection and elimination.
[src:gdb-debugging/debugging] An early example of anti-debugging existed in early versions of Microsoft Word which, if a debugger was detected, produced a message that said, "The tree of evil bears bitter fruit.
[src:gdb-debugging/debugging] Now trashing program disk.", after which it caused the floppy disk drive to emit alarming noises with the intent of scaring the user away from attempting it again.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] In programming and software development, **fuzzing** or **fuzz testing** is an automated software testing technique that involves providing invalid, unexpected, or random data as inputs to a computer program.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] The program is then monitored for exceptions such as crashes, failing built-in code assertions, or potential memory leaks.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] Typically, fuzzers are used to test programs that take structured inputs.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] This structure is specified, such as in a file format or protocol and distinguishes valid from invalid input.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] An effective fuzzer generates semi-valid inputs that are "valid enough" in that they are not directly rejected by the parser, but do create unexpected behaviors deeper in the program and are "invalid enough" to expose corner cases that have not been properly dealt with.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] For the purpose of security, input that crosses a trust boundary is often the most useful.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] For example, it is more important to fuzz code that handles a file uploaded by any user than it is to fuzz the code that parses a configuration file that is accessible only to a privileged user.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] The term "fuzz" originates from a 1988 class project in the graduate Advanced Operating Systems class (CS736), taught by Prof.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] Barton Miller at the University of Wisconsin, whose results were subsequently published in 1990.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] To fuzz test a UNIX utility meant to automatically generate random input and command-line parameters for the utility.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] The project was designed to test the reliability of UNIX command line programs by executing a large number of random inputs in quick succession until they crashed.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] Miller's team was able to crash 25 to 33 percent of the utilities that they tested.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] They then debugged each of the crashes to determine the cause and categorized each detected failure.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] To allow other researchers to conduct similar experiments with other software, the source code of the tools, the test procedures, and the raw result data were made publicly available.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] This early fuzzing would now be called black box, generational, unstructured (dumb or "classic") fuzzing.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] Barton Miller, "In the process of writing the project description, I needed to give this kind of testing a name.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] I wanted a name that would evoke the feeling of random, unstructured data.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] A key contribution of this early work was simple (almost simplistic) oracle.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] A program failed its test if it crashed or hung under the random input and was considered to have passed otherwise.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] While test oracles can be challenging to construct, the oracle for this early fuzz testing was simple and universal to apply.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] In April 2012, Google announced ClusterFuzz, a cloud-based fuzzing infrastructure for security-critical components of the Chromium web browser.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] Security researchers can upload their own fuzzers and collect bug bounties if ClusterFuzz finds a crash with the uploaded fuzzer.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] In September 2014, Shellshock was disclosed as a family of security bugs in the widely used UNIX Bash shell; most vulnerabilities of Shellshock were found using the fuzzer AFL.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] (Many Internet-facing services, such as some web server deployments, use Bash to process certain requests, allowing an attacker to cause vulnerable versions of Bash to execute arbitrary commands.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] In April 2015, Hanno Böck showed how the fuzzer AFL could have found the 2014 Heartbleed vulnerability.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] (The Heartbleed vulnerability was disclosed in April 2014.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] It is a serious vulnerability that allows adversaries to decipher otherwise encrypted communication.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] The vulnerability was accidentally introduced into OpenSSL which implements TLS and is used by the majority of the servers on the internet.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] In August 2016, the Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency (DARPA) held the finals of the first Cyber Grand Challenge, a fully automated capture-the-flag competition that lasted 11 hours.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] The objective was to develop automatic defense systems that can discover, exploit, and correct software flaws in real-time.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] Fuzzing was used as an effective offense strategy to discover flaws in the software of the opponents.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] It showed tremendous potential in the automation of vulnerability detection.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] The winner was a system called "Mayhem" developed by the team ForAllSecure led by David Brumley.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] In September 2016, Microsoft announced Project Springfield, a cloud-based fuzz testing service for finding security critical bugs in software.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] In December 2016, Google announced OSS-Fuzz which allows for continuous fuzzing of several security-critical open-source projects.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] At Black Hat 2018, Christopher Domas demonstrated the use of fuzzing to expose the existence of a hidden RISC core in a processor.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] This core was able to bypass existing security checks to execute Ring 0 commands from Ring 3.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] In September 2020, Microsoft released OneFuzz, a self-hosted fuzzing-as-a-service platform that automates the detection of software bugs.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] It was archived three years later on November 1, 2023.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] Testing programs with random inputs dates back to the 1950s when data was still stored on punched cards.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] Programmers would use punched cards that were pulled from the trash or card decks of random numbers as input to computer programs.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] If an execution revealed undesired behavior, a bug had been detected.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] The execution of random inputs is also called random testing, monkey testing or Monte Carlo debugging (in analogy to Monte Carlo methods).
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] In 1981, Duran and Ntafos formally investigated the effectiveness of testing a program with random inputs.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] While random testing had been widely perceived to be the worst means of testing a program, the authors could show that it is a cost-effective alternative to more systematic testing techniques.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] In 1983, Steve Capps at Apple developed "The Monkey", a tool that would generate random inputs for classic Mac OS applications, such as MacPaint.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] The figurative "monkey" refers to the infinite monkey theorem which states that a monkey hitting keys at random on a typewriter keyboard for an infinite amount of time will eventually type out the entire works of Shakespeare.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] In the case of testing, the monkey would write the particular sequence of inputs that would trigger a crash.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] In 1991, the crashme tool was released, which was intended to test the robustness of Unix and Unix-like operating systems by randomly executing systems calls with randomly chosen parameters.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] A fuzzer can be dumb (unstructured) or smart (structured) depending on whether it is aware of input structure.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] A fuzzer can be white-, grey-, or black-box, depending on whether it is aware of program structure.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] A mutation-based fuzzer leverages an existing corpus of seed inputs during fuzzing.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] It generates inputs by modifying (or rather mutating) the provided seeds.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] For example, when fuzzing the image library libpng, the user would provide a set of valid PNG image files as seeds while a mutation-based fuzzer would modify these seeds to produce semi-valid variants of each seed.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] The corpus of seed files may contain thousands of potentially similar inputs.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] Automated seed selection (or test suite reduction) allows users to pick the best seeds in order to maximize the total number of bugs found during a fuzz campaign.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] A generation-based fuzzer generates inputs from scratch.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] For instance, a smart generation-based fuzzer takes the input model that was provided by the user to generate new inputs.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] Unlike mutation-based fuzzers, a generation-based fuzzer does not depend on the existence or quality of a corpus of seed inputs.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] Some fuzzers have the capability to do both, to generate inputs from scratch and to generate inputs by mutation of existing seeds.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] Typically, fuzzers are used to generate inputs for programs that take structured inputs, such as a file, a sequence of keyboard or mouse events, or a sequence of messages.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] This structure distinguishes valid input that is accepted and processed by the program from invalid input that is quickly rejected by the program.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] What constitutes a valid input may be explicitly specified in an input model.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] Examples of input models are formal grammars, file formats, GUI-models, and network protocols.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] Even items not normally considered as input can be fuzzed, such as the contents of databases, shared memory, environment variables or the precise interleaving of threads.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] An effective fuzzer generates semi-valid inputs that are "valid enough" so that they are not directly rejected from the parser and "invalid enough" so that they might stress corner cases and exercise interesting program behaviours.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] A smart (model-based, grammar-based, or protocol-based) fuzzer leverages the input model to generate a greater proportion of valid inputs.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] For instance, if the input can be modelled as an abstract syntax tree, then a smart mutation-based fuzzer would employ random transformations to move complete subtrees from one node to another.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] If the input can be modelled by a formal grammar, a smart generation-based fuzzer would instantiate the production rules to generate inputs that are valid with respect to the grammar.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] However, generally the input model must be explicitly provided, which is difficult to do when the model is proprietary, unknown, or very complex.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] If a large corpus of valid and invalid inputs is available, a grammar induction technique, such as Angluin's L* algorithm, would be able to generate an input model.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] A dumb fuzzer does not require the input model and can thus be employed to fuzz a wider variety of programs.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] For instance, AFL is a dumb mutation-based fuzzer that modifies a seed file by flipping random bits, by substituting random bytes with "interesting" values, and by moving or deleting blocks of data.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] However, a dumb fuzzer might generate a lower proportion of valid inputs and stress the parser code rather than the main components of a program.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] The disadvantage of dumb fuzzers can be illustrated by means of the construction of a valid checksum for a cyclic redundancy check (CRC).
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] A CRC is an error-detecting code that ensures that the integrity of the data contained in the input file is preserved during transmission.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] A checksum is computed over the input data and recorded in the file.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] When the program processes the received file and the recorded checksum does not match the re-computed checksum, then the file is rejected as invalid.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] Now, a fuzzer that is unaware of the CRC is unlikely to generate the correct checksum.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] However, there are attempts to identify and re-compute a potential checksum in the mutated input, once a dumb mutation-based fuzzer has modified the protected data.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] Typically, a fuzzer is considered more effective if it achieves a higher degree of code coverage.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] The rationale is, if a fuzzer does not exercise certain structural elements in the program, then it is also not able to reveal bugs that are hiding in these elements.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] Some program elements are considered more critical than others.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] For instance, a division operator might cause a division by zero error, or a system call may crash the program.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] A black-box fuzzer treats the program as a black box and is unaware of internal program structure.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] For instance, a random testing tool that generates inputs at random is considered a blackbox fuzzer.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] Hence, a blackbox fuzzer can execute several hundred inputs per second, can be easily parallelized, and can scale to programs of arbitrary size.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] However, blackbox fuzzers may only scratch the surface and expose "shallow" bugs.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] Hence, there are attempts to develop blackbox fuzzers that can incrementally learn about the internal structure (and behavior) of a program during fuzzing by observing the program's output given an input.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] For instance, LearnLib employs active learning to generate an automaton that represents the behavior of a web application.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] A white-box fuzzer leverages program analysis to systematically increase code coverage or to reach certain critical program locations.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] For instance, SAGE leverages symbolic execution to systematically explore different paths in the program (a technique known as concolic execution).
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] If the program's specification is available, a whitebox fuzzer might leverage techniques from model-based testing to generate inputs and check the program outputs against the program specification.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] A whitebox fuzzer can be very effective at exposing bugs that hide deep in the program.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] However, the time used for analysis (of the program or its specification) can become prohibitive.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] If the whitebox fuzzer takes relatively too long to generate an input, a blackbox fuzzer will be more efficient.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] Hence, there are attempts to combine the efficiency of blackbox fuzzers and the effectiveness of whitebox fuzzers.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] A gray-box fuzzer leverages instrumentation rather than program analysis to glean information about the program.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] For instance, AFL and libFuzzer utilize lightweight instrumentation to trace basic block transitions exercised by an input.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] This leads to a reasonable performance overhead but informs the fuzzer about the increase in code coverage during fuzzing, which makes gray-box fuzzers extremely efficient vulnerability detection tools.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] Fuzzing is used mostly as an automated technique to expose vulnerabilities in security-critical programs that might be exploited with malicious intent.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] More generally, fuzzing is used to demonstrate the presence of bugs rather than their absence.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] Running a fuzzing campaign for several weeks without finding a bug does not prove the program correct.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] After all, the program may still fail for an input that has not been executed, yet; executing a program for all inputs is prohibitively expensive.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] If the objective is to prove a program correct for all inputs, a formal specification must exist and techniques from formal methods must be used.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] In order to expose bugs, a fuzzer must be able to distinguish expected (normal) from unexpected (buggy) program behavior.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] However, a machine cannot always distinguish a bug from a feature.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] In automated software testing, this is also called the test oracle problem.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] Typically, a fuzzer distinguishes between crashing and non-crashing inputs in the absence of specifications and to use a simple and objective measure.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] Crashes can be easily identified and might indicate potential vulnerabilities (e.g., denial of service or arbitrary code execution).
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] However, the absence of a crash does not indicate the absence of a vulnerability.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] For instance, a program written in C may or may not crash when an input causes a buffer overflow.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] Rather the program's behavior is undefined.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] To make a fuzzer more sensitive to failures other than crashes, sanitizers can be used to inject assertions that crash the program when a failure is detected.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] Fuzzing can also be used to detect "differential" bugs if a reference implementation is available.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] For automated regression testing, the generated inputs are executed on two versions of the same program.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] For automated differential testing, the generated inputs are executed on two implementations of the same program (e.g., lighttpd and httpd are both implementations of a web server).
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] If the two variants produce different output for the same input, then one may be buggy and should be examined more closely.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] Static program analysis analyzes a program without actually executing it.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] This might lead to false positives where the tool reports problems with the program that do not actually exist.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] Fuzzing in combination with dynamic program analysis can be used to try to generate an input that actually witnesses the reported problem.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] Modern web browsers undergo extensive fuzzing.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] The Chromium code of Google Chrome is continuously fuzzed by the Chrome Security Team with 15,000 cores.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] For Microsoft Edge [Legacy] and Internet Explorer, Microsoft performed fuzzed testing with 670 machine-years during product development, generating more than 400 billion DOM manipulations from 1 billion HTML files.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] A fuzzer produces a large number of inputs in a relatively short time.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] For instance, in 2016 the Google OSS-fuzz project produced around 4 trillion inputs a week.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] Hence, many fuzzers provide a toolchain that automates otherwise manual and tedious tasks which follow the automated generation of failure-inducing inputs.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] Automated bug triage is used to group a large number of failure-inducing inputs by root cause and to prioritize each individual bug by severity.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] A fuzzer produces a large number of inputs, and many of the failure-inducing ones may effectively expose the same software bug.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] Only some of these bugs are security-critical and should be patched with higher priority.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] For instance the CERT Coordination Center provides the Linux triage tools which group crashing inputs by the produced stack trace and lists each group according to their probability to be exploitable.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] Previously unreported, triaged bugs might be automatically reported to a bug tracking system.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] For instance, OSS-Fuzz runs large-scale, long-running fuzzing campaigns for several security-critical software projects where each previously unreported, distinct bug is reported directly to a bug tracker.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] The OSS-Fuzz bug tracker automatically informs the maintainer of the vulnerable software and checks in regular intervals whether the bug has been fixed in the most recent revision using the uploaded minimized failure-inducing input.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] Automated input minimization (or test case reduction) is an automated debugging technique to isolate that part of the failure-inducing input that is actually inducing the failure.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] If the failure-inducing input is large and mostly malformed, it might be difficult for a developer to understand what exactly is causing the bug.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] Given the failure-inducing input, an automated minimization tool would remove as many input bytes as possible while still reproducing the original bug.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] For instance, Delta Debugging is an automated input minimization technique that employs an extended binary search algorithm to find such a minimal input.
[src:gdb-debugging/fuzzing] The following is a list of fuzzers described as "popular", "widely used", or similar in the academic literature.
[src:gdb-debugging/gnu-debugger] The **GNU Debugger** (**GDB**) is a portable debugger that runs on many Unix-like systems and works for many programming languages, including Ada, Assembly, C, C++, D, Fortran, Haskell, Go, Objective-C, OpenCL C, Modula-2, Pascal, Rust, and partially others.
[src:gdb-debugging/gnu-debugger] It detects problems in a program while letting it run and allows users to examine program variables and machine registers.
[src:gdb-debugging/gnu-debugger] GDB was first written by Richard Stallman in 1986 as part of his GNU system, after his GNU Emacs was "reasonably stable".
[src:gdb-debugging/gnu-debugger] GDB is free software released under the GNU General Public License (GPL).
[src:gdb-debugging/gnu-debugger] It was modeled after the DBX debugger, which came with Berkeley Unix distributions.
[src:gdb-debugging/gnu-debugger] From 1990 to 1993 it was maintained by John Gilmore.
[src:gdb-debugging/gnu-debugger] Now it is maintained by the GDB Steering Committee which is appointed by the Free Software Foundation.
[src:gdb-debugging/gnu-debugger] GDB offers extensive facilities for tracing, examining and altering the execution of computer programs.
[src:gdb-debugging/gnu-debugger] The user can monitor and modify the values of programs' internal variables, and even call functions independently of the program's normal behavior.
[src:gdb-debugging/gnu-debugger] GDB target processors (as of 2003) include: Alpha, ARM, AVR, H8/300, Altera Nios/Nios II, System/370, System/390, x86 (32-bit and 64-bit), IA-64 "Itanium", Motorola 68k, MIPS, PA-RISC, PowerPC, RISC-V, SuperH, SPARC, and VAX.
[src:gdb-debugging/gnu-debugger] Lesser-known target processors supported in the standard release have included A29K, ARC, ETRAX CRIS, D10V, D30V, FR-30, FR-V, Intel i960, 68HC11, Motorola 88000, MCORE, MN10200, MN10300, NS32k, Stormy16, and Z8000 (newer releases will likely not support some of these).
[src:gdb-debugging/gnu-debugger] GDB has compiled-in simulators for most targets.
[src:gdb-debugging/gnu-debugger] Both the **next *n*** and **step *n*** command can be used to advance execution over the next n statements.
[src:gdb-debugging/gnu-debugger] The difference between the commands is that step will follow the flow of execution into the internals of any function call whereas next will execute the whole function and proceed to the next statement within the current routine.
[src:gdb-debugging/gnu-debugger] The **jump *location*** command is used either to skip over a section of problematic code or go back to a previous statement in order to review execution again.
[src:gdb-debugging/gnu-debugger] The specified location may correspond to different parts of the executing program, but unexpected results may occur for those not accustomed to machine code.
[src:gdb-debugging/gnu-debugger] When a program is halted in mid execution the **print** (abbreviated as **p**) command can be used to display the value of a variable or an expression using C or C++ syntax.
[src:gdb-debugging/gnu-debugger] The **x** command (meaning "examine") is similar but its argument is an address in memory including address expressions.
[src:gdb-debugging/gnu-debugger] Both commands use flags to indicate presentation format of the output though there are some differences as **x** allows one to specify the number of bytes.
[src:gdb-debugging/gnu-debugger] Additionally the **call** command invokes both library and user written functions and the returned value will be displayed.
[src:gdb-debugging/gnu-debugger] Values displayed are automatically assigned to special *value history* variables which begin with a $ sign followed by a sequence number which can then be redisplayed using **print**.
[src:gdb-debugging/gnu-debugger] One can also use the **set** command to create *convenience variables* for use during a gdb session.
[src:gdb-debugging/gnu-debugger] If the argument of **print** is an array or struct all elements will be output.
[src:gdb-debugging/gnu-debugger] Breakpoints and watchpoints are used when one needs to examine a program prior to a known situation where things are likely to go wrong.
[src:gdb-debugging/gnu-debugger] Both break and watchpoints issued integer identification numbers, 1, 2, 3... which can be used to enable, disable or delete them.
[src:gdb-debugging/gnu-debugger] The command **info break**|**watch** displays all breakpoints and their current status.
[src:gdb-debugging/gnu-debugger] Breakpoints are set to halt the flow of execution either on specific line numbers in one's code or on entry to a function when run within the debugger i.e.: **break** *sourcefile*:42 will stop on line 42 of the specified file.
[src:gdb-debugging/gnu-debugger] If the file name is omitted the reference is to the current file.
[src:gdb-debugging/gnu-debugger] The **condition** *breakNum* *expression* command allows one to add conditions to an established breakpoint.
[src:gdb-debugging/gnu-debugger] Watchpoints halt the flow of execution when the value of a variable or an expression changes, irrespective of where in the program it occurs.
[src:gdb-debugging/gnu-debugger] By default, where possible, gdb monitors the memory location where the change takes place, a useful feature given that multiple pointers may refer to the same address.
[src:gdb-debugging/gnu-debugger] Conversely a software watchpoint, which are slower, track just the variables.
[src:gdb-debugging/gnu-debugger] The rwatch and awatch commands will halt the program whenever the memory location or variable is read.
[src:gdb-debugging/gnu-debugger] Another conditional feature of both watches and breakpoints is the command **ignore** *breakNum* *count* which disregards the halting criteria until count execution passes.
[src:gdb-debugging/gnu-debugger] The display command primes gdb to automatically output the value of an expression each time it stops.
[src:gdb-debugging/gnu-debugger] Multiple display commands are cumulative and the output can be formatted using the same flags available to the x command.
[src:gdb-debugging/gnu-debugger] When a program is halted it may be several layers deep in function calls.
[src:gdb-debugging/gnu-debugger] Each level of function call is called a frame and the collection of frames is called a frame stack.
[src:gdb-debugging/gnu-debugger] When execution is halted one can navigate either up or down to a specific frame in order to examine the value of variables or expressions at a particular level which is useful to assist debugging programs.
[src:gdb-debugging/gnu-debugger] The **backtrace** command will provide a list of all of the frames in the stack.
[src:gdb-debugging/gnu-debugger] The **info args** command displays all of the arguments passed to the current frame and the **info local** command displays a list of the variables available to it along with their values.
[src:gdb-debugging/gnu-debugger] GDB includes the ability to define command routines that can be used to automate frequently repeated sets of gdb instructions.
[src:gdb-debugging/gnu-debugger] These consisting of gdb commands placed between define and end statements.
[src:gdb-debugging/gnu-debugger] Parameters to these routines are not declared by name however they are passed in special variables $arg1, $arg2, $arg3... with special variable $argc representing the number of command line arguments.
[src:gdb-debugging/gnu-debugger] Additionally gdb includes if/else and while blocks terminated by end statements as well as loop_break and loop_continue statements to manage flow of control.
[src:gdb-debugging/gnu-debugger] Command definitions placed in the local file **.gdbinit** are automatically loaded at the beginning of the gdb session.
[src:gdb-debugging/gnu-debugger] Command definitions can also be saved in ordinary files and loaded using the source command.
[src:gdb-debugging/gnu-debugger] As of version 7.0 new features include support for Python scripting and as of version 7.8 GNU Guile scripting as well which is based on the Scheme (programming language).
[src:gdb-debugging/gnu-debugger] Since version 7.0, support for "reversible debugging" — allowing a debugging session to step backward, much like rewinding a crashed program to see what happened — is available.
[src:gdb-debugging/gnu-debugger] The feature is highly memory intensive and slows execution with a default limit of 20,000 instructions.
[src:gdb-debugging/gnu-debugger] The recommended procedure is to set breakpoints before and after the suspected problem, then issue the **record** command when the program stops at first one.
[src:gdb-debugging/gnu-debugger] Continue execution to the 2nd breakpoint.
[src:gdb-debugging/gnu-debugger] GDB offers a "remote" mode often used when debugging embedded systems.
[src:gdb-debugging/gnu-debugger] Remote operation is when GDB runs on one machine and the program being debugged runs on another.
[src:gdb-debugging/gnu-debugger] GDB can communicate to the remote "stub" that understands GDB protocol through a serial device or TCP/IP.
[src:gdb-debugging/gnu-debugger] A stub program can be created by linking to the appropriate stub files provided with GDB, which implement the target side of the communication protocol.
[src:gdb-debugging/gnu-debugger] Alternatively, gdbserver can be used to remotely debug the program without needing to change it in any way.
[src:gdb-debugging/gnu-debugger] The same mode is also used by KGDB for debugging a running Linux kernel on the source level with gdb.
[src:gdb-debugging/gnu-debugger] With KGDB, kernel developers can debug a kernel in much the same way as they debug application programs.
[src:gdb-debugging/gnu-debugger] It makes it possible to place breakpoints in kernel code, step through the code, and observe variables.
[src:gdb-debugging/gnu-debugger] On architectures where hardware debugging registers are available, watchpoints can be set which trigger breakpoints when specified memory addresses are executed or accessed.
[src:gdb-debugging/gnu-debugger] KGDB requires an additional machine which is connected to the machine to be debugged using a serial cable or Ethernet.
[src:gdb-debugging/gnu-debugger] On FreeBSD, it is also possible to debug using FireWire direct memory access (DMA).
[src:gdb-debugging/gnu-debugger] The debugger does not contain its own graphical user interface, and defaults to a command-line interface, although it does contain a text user interface.
[src:gdb-debugging/gnu-debugger] Several front-ends have been built for it, such as UltraGDB, Xxgdb, Data Display Debugger (DDD), Nemiver, KDbg, the Xcode debugger, GDBtk/Insight, Gede, Seer, and HP Wildebeest Debugger GUI (WDB GUI).
[src:gdb-debugging/gnu-debugger] IDEs such as Codelite, Code::Blocks, Dev-C++, Geany, GNAT Programming Studio (GPS), KDevelop, Qt Creator, Lazarus, MonoDevelop, Eclipse, NetBeans, and Visual Studio can interface with GDB.
[src:gdb-debugging/gnu-debugger] GNU Emacs has a "GUD mode" and tools for Vim exist (e.g. clewn).
[src:gdb-debugging/gnu-debugger] These offer facilities similar to debuggers found in IDEs.
[src:gdb-debugging/gnu-debugger] Some other debugging tools have been designed to work with GDB, such as memory leak detectors.
[src:gdb-debugging/gnu-debugger] GDB uses a system call named ptrace (the name is an abbreviation of "process trace") to observe and control the execution of another process, and examine and change the process's memory and registers.
[src:gdb-debugging/gnu-debugger] A breakpoint is implemented by replacing an instruction at a given memory address with another special instruction.
[src:gdb-debugging/gnu-debugger] Executing breakpoint instruction causes SIGTRAP.
[src:gdb-debugging/memory-debugger] A **memory debugger** is a debugger for finding software memory problems such as memory leaks and buffer overflows.
[src:gdb-debugging/memory-debugger] These are due to bugs related to the allocation and deallocation of dynamic memory.
[src:gdb-debugging/memory-debugger] Programs written in languages that have garbage collection, such as managed code, might also need memory debuggers, e.g. for memory leaks due to "living" references in collections.
[src:gdb-debugging/memory-debugger] Memory debuggers work by monitoring memory access, allocations, and deallocation of memory.
[src:gdb-debugging/memory-debugger] Many memory debuggers require applications to be recompiled with special dynamic memory allocation libraries, whose APIs are mostly compatible with conventional dynamic memory allocation libraries, or else use dynamic linking.
[src:gdb-debugging/memory-debugger] Electric Fence is such a debugger which debugs memory allocation with malloc.
[src:gdb-debugging/memory-debugger] Valgrind) work by running the executable in a virtual machine-like environment, monitoring memory access, allocation and deallocation so that no recompilation with special memory allocation libraries is required.
[src:gdb-debugging/memory-debugger] Finding memory issues such as leaks can be extremely time-consuming as they may not manifest themselves except under certain conditions.
[src:gdb-debugging/memory-debugger] Using a tool to detect memory misuse makes the process much faster and easier.
[src:gdb-debugging/memory-debugger] As abnormally high memory utilization can be a contributing factor in software aging, memory debuggers can help programmers to avoid software anomalies that would exhaust the computer system memory, thus ensuring high reliability of the software even for long runtimes.
[src:gdb-debugging/memory-debugger] Some static analysis tools can also help find memory errors.
[src:gdb-debugging/memory-debugger] Memory debuggers operate as part of an application while its running while static code analysis is performed by analyzing the code without executing it.
[src:gdb-debugging/memory-debugger] These different techniques will typically find different instances of problems, and using them both together yields the best result.
[src:gdb-debugging/memory-debugger] This is a list of tools useful for memory debugging.
[src:gdb-debugging/memory-debugger] A profiler can be used in conjunction with a memory debugger.
[src:gdb-debugging/stack-trace] In computing, a **stack trace** (also called **stack backtrace** or **stack traceback**) is a report of the active stack frames at a certain point in time during the execution of a program.
[src:gdb-debugging/stack-trace] When a program is run, memory is often dynamically allocated in two places: the stack and the heap.
[src:gdb-debugging/stack-trace] Memory is continuously allocated on a stack but not on a heap.
[src:gdb-debugging/stack-trace] Stack also refers to a programming construct, thus to differentiate it, this stack is referred to as the program's **function call stack**.
[src:gdb-debugging/stack-trace] Technically, once a block of memory has been allocated on the stack, it cannot be easily removed as there can be other blocks of memory that were allocated after it.
[src:gdb-debugging/stack-trace] Each time a function is called in a program, a block of memory called an **activation record** is allocated on top of the call stack.
[src:gdb-debugging/stack-trace] Generally, the activation record stores the function's arguments and local variables.
[src:gdb-debugging/stack-trace] What exactly it contains and how it's laid out is determined by the calling convention.
[src:gdb-debugging/stack-trace] Programmers commonly use stack tracing during interactive and post-mortem debugging.
[src:gdb-debugging/stack-trace] End-users may see a stack trace displayed as part of an error message, which the user can then report to a programmer.
[src:gdb-debugging/stack-trace] A stack trace allows tracking the sequence of nested functions called - up to the point where the stack trace is generated.
[src:gdb-debugging/stack-trace] In a post-mortem scenario this extends up to the function where the failure occurred (but was not necessarily caused).
[src:gdb-debugging/stack-trace] Sibling calls do not appear in a stack trace.
[src:gdb-debugging/stack-trace] Many programming languages, including Java and C#, have built-in support for retrieving the current stack trace via system calls.
[src:gdb-debugging/stack-trace] Before `std::stacktrace` was added in standard library as a container for `std::stacktrace_entry`, pre-C++23 has no built-in support for doing this, but C++ users can retrieve stack traces with (for example) the stacktrace library.
[src:gdb-debugging/stack-trace] In JavaScript, exceptions hold a `stack` property that contain the stack from the place where it was thrown.
[src:gdb-debugging/stack-trace] As an example, the following Python program contains an error.
[src:gdb-debugging/stack-trace] Running the program under the standard Python interpreter produces the following error message.
[src:gdb-debugging/stack-trace] The stack trace shows where the error occurs, namely in the `c` function.
[src:gdb-debugging/stack-trace] It also shows that the `c` function was called by `b`, which was called by `a`, which was in turn called by the code on line 16 (the last line) of the program.
[src:gdb-debugging/stack-trace] The activation records for each of these three functions would be arranged in a stack such that the `a` function would occupy the bottom of the stack and the `c` function would occupy the top of the stack.
[src:gdb-debugging/stack-trace] The exception lists functions in descending order, so the most-inner call is first.
[src:gdb-debugging/stack-trace] Java also allows retrieving the current stack trace using `java.lang.Thread::getStackTrace()`, or displaying the stack trace at an error using `java.lang.Throwable::printStackTrace()`.
[src:gdb-debugging/stack-trace] A stack trace in Java is represented as `java.lang.StackTraceElement[]`, an array.
[src:gdb-debugging/stack-trace] C does not have native support for obtaining stack traces, but libraries such as glibc provide this functionality.
[src:gdb-debugging/stack-trace] In C and C++, some compiler optimizations may interfere with the call stack information that can be recovered at runtime.
[src:gdb-debugging/stack-trace] For instance, inlining can cause missing stack frames, tail call optimizations can replace one stack frame with another, and frame pointer elimination can prevent call stack analysis tools from correctly interpreting the contents of the call stack.
[src:gdb-debugging/stack-trace] For example, glibc's `backtrace()` function returns an output with the program function and memory address.
[src:gdb-debugging/stack-trace] Prior to C++23, no mechanisms in C++ existed to obtain stack traces, but third-party libraries like *Boost.Stacktrace* offered stack traces.
[src:gdb-debugging/stack-trace] C# offers a `System.Diagnostics.StackTrace` class.
[src:gdb-debugging/stack-trace] Functions that use the panic macro are "unrecoverable" and the current thread will become poisoned experiencing stack unwinding.
[src:gdb-debugging/stack-trace] Functions that return a `std::result::Result` are "recoverable" and can be handled gracefully.
[src:gdb-debugging/stack-trace] However, recoverable errors cannot generate a stack trace as they are manually added and not a result of a runtime error.
[src:gdb-debugging/stack-trace] As of June 2021, Rust has experimental support for stack traces on unrecoverable errors.
[src:gdb-debugging/stack-trace] Rust supports printing to stderr when a thread panics, but it must be enabled by setting the `RUST_BACKTRACE` environment variable.
[src:gdb-debugging/stack-trace] When enabled, such backtraces look similar to below, with the most recent call first.
[src:gdb-debugging/valgrind] Valgrind was originally designed to be a freely licensed memory debugging tool for Linux on x86, but has since evolved to become a generic framework for creating dynamic analysis tools such as checkers and profilers.
[src:gdb-debugging/valgrind] Valgrind is in essence a virtual machine using just-in-time compilation techniques, including dynamic recompilation.
[src:gdb-debugging/valgrind] Nothing from the original program ever gets run directly on the host processor.
[src:gdb-debugging/valgrind] Instead, Valgrind first translates the program into a temporary, simpler form called intermediate representation (IR), which is a processor-neutral, static single assignment form-based form.
[src:gdb-debugging/valgrind] After the conversion, a tool (see below) is free to do whatever transformations it would like on the IR, before Valgrind translates the IR back into machine code and lets the host processor run it.
[src:gdb-debugging/valgrind] Valgrind recompiles binary code to run on host and target (or simulated) CPUs of the same architecture.
[src:gdb-debugging/valgrind] It also includes a GDB stub to allow debugging of the target program as it runs in Valgrind, with "monitor commands" that allow querying the Valgrind tool for various information.
[src:gdb-debugging/valgrind] A considerable amount of performance is lost in these transformations (and usually, the code the tool inserts); usually, code run with Valgrind and the "none" tool (which does nothing to the IR) runs at 20% to 25% of the speed of the normal program.
[src:gdb-debugging/valgrind] There are multiple tools included with Valgrind (and several external ones).
[src:gdb-debugging/valgrind] The default (and most used) tool is *Memcheck*.
[src:gdb-debugging/valgrind] As data is moved around or manipulated, the instrumentation code keeps track of the A and V bits, so they are always correct on a single-bit level.
[src:gdb-debugging/valgrind] In addition, Memcheck replaces the standard C++ allocators and C memory allocator with its own implementation, which also includes *memory guards* around all allocated blocks (with the A bits set to "invalid").
[src:gdb-debugging/valgrind] This feature enables Memcheck to detect off-by-one errors where a program reads or writes outside an allocated block by a small amount.
[src:gdb-debugging/valgrind] Programs running under Memcheck usually run 20–30 times slower than running outside Valgrind and use more memory (there is a memory penalty per allocation).
[src:gdb-debugging/valgrind] Thus, few developers run their code under Memcheck (or any other Valgrind tool) all the time.
[src:gdb-debugging/valgrind] They most commonly use such tools either to trace down some specific bug, or to verify that there are no latent bugs (of the kind Memcheck can detect) in the code.
[src:gdb-debugging/valgrind] Part of the core of Valgrind always has to perform some checking on file descriptors (for instance to prevent the test executable from affecting Valgrind's log file or other output files).
[src:gdb-debugging/valgrind] Checking can also be done for more general user errors affecting file descriptors.
[src:gdb-debugging/valgrind] Starting with Valgrind 3.24 these errors are handled by Valgrind in the same way as other errors.
[src:gdb-debugging/valgrind] That means that you can generate and use suppressions with them.
[src:gdb-debugging/valgrind] Valgrind 3.25 added a feature where you can change the behaviour of functions that create file descriptors.
[src:gdb-debugging/valgrind] The default behaviour is the same as POSIX, which will return the lowest available file descriptor, potentially recycling closed file descriptors.
[src:gdb-debugging/valgrind] There is the risk that the test executable will accidentally and erroneously use such a recycled file descriptor.
[src:gdb-debugging/valgrind] Valgrind's --modify-fds option changes the behaviour to no longer respect the POSIX standard.
[src:gdb-debugging/valgrind] Instead it will try to create a new file descriptor for each request.
[src:gdb-debugging/valgrind] There are also several externally developed tools available.
[src:gdb-debugging/valgrind] One such tool is ThreadSanitizer, another detector of race conditions.
[src:gdb-debugging/valgrind] As of version 3.4.0, Valgrind supports Linux on x86, x86-64 and PowerPC.
[src:gdb-debugging/valgrind] Support for Linux on ARMv7 (used for example in certain smartphones) was added in version 3.6.0.
[src:gdb-debugging/valgrind] From version 3.7.0 the ARM/Android platform support was added.
[src:gdb-debugging/valgrind] Support for Solaris was added in version 3.11.0.
[src:gdb-debugging/valgrind] Support for OS X was added in version 3.5.0.
[src:gdb-debugging/valgrind] Support for FreeBSD x86 and amd64 was added in version 3.18.0.
[src:gdb-debugging/valgrind] Support for FreeBSD aarch64 was added in version 3.23.0.
[src:gdb-debugging/valgrind] Support for macOS 10.13 was improved and support for macOS 10.14, 10.15, 11, 12 and 13 were added in Valgrind 3.27.
[src:gdb-debugging/valgrind] There are unofficial ports to other Unix-like platforms (like OpenBSD, NetBSD, DragonFly BSD and QNX).
[src:gdb-debugging/valgrind] The name Valgrind refers to the main entrance to Valhalla in Norse mythology.
[src:gdb-debugging/valgrind] During development (before release) the project was named Heimdall; however, the name would have conflicted with a security package.
[src:gdb-debugging/valgrind] The original author of Valgrind is Julian Seward, who in 2006 won a Google-O'Reilly Open Source Award for his work on Valgrind.
[src:gdb-debugging/valgrind] Several others have also made significant contributions, including Nicholas Nethercote, Bart Van Assche, Florian Krohm, Tom Hughes, Philippe Waroquiers, Mark Wielaard, Paul Floyd, Petar Jovanovic, Carl Love, Petr Pavlu and Ivo Raisr.
[src:gdb-debugging/valgrind] It is used by a number of Linux-based projects.
[src:gdb-debugging/valgrind] In addition to the performance penalty, an important limitation of Memcheck is its inability to detect all cases of bounds errors in the use of static or stack-allocated data.
[src:gdb-debugging/valgrind] The inability to detect all errors involving the access of stack allocated data is especially noteworthy since certain types of stack errors make software vulnerable to the classic stack smashing exploit.
